<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> In the Deep End: Running with Isengard Trackers.<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11682'>Paul "Hetfool" Twomey</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11682&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 18, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> There are a huge number of vastly powerful and aggressive deck strategies for the shadow player now, and the new site path provides even more twilight and benefit than ever before. As a disclaimer, the Isengard Tracker strategy is not the best nor is it the be all and end all, it is however my favourite so any bias displayed in this article needs to have this consideration attached.<br>
<br>
These guys are actually quite a small part of the whole Isengard set and may get a look in the Helms Deep expansions. But without wasting any time and with out stating the obvious (the new trackers are fierce instead of damage+1) here is a list of the Minions available to this strategy and a small description of each (in no particular order):<br>
<br>
Mauhur, Patrol Leader (Cost 3/Str 9/Vit 2): Removing 2 during a skirmish to prevent all wounds to a Tracker is a really potent ability, this will become apparent later on in this article.<br>
<br>
Ugluck, Servant of Saruman (4/9/3): Once called a poor mans Lurtz this guy is far more powerful then he appears. Not only does he reduce the roaming cost of all Trackers to 0, but he becomes str+3 if you can spot 2 trackers (this includes himself) and damage+1 if you spot 3. In combination with his sword, which I will look at later, this guy becomes one of the best minion rares.<br>
<br>
Uruk Chaser (4/9/2): A fierce bonus minion, during fierce skirmishes this guy is str+2.<br>
<br>
Uruk Follower (5/10/3): Prevent unbound Hobbits from being discarded; hey a one card bane for unbound Hobbit decks. Then if an unbound Hobbit is killed you can exert Follower to add a burden.<br>
<br>
Uruk Foot Soldier (1/5/1): This puny creature with more uses than just a lacky (to be explored later) is another fierce bonus minion, during fierce skirmishes this guy is str+3 and damage+1.<br>
<br>
Uruk Hunter (6/12/3): Prevent unbound Hobbits from being discarded; hey another one card bane for unbound Hobbit decks. Then if an unbound Hobbit is killed you can exert Hunter to exhaust a minion.<br>
<br>
Uruk Plains Runner (2/7/1): Similar to the Foot Soldier in every way, gaining str+3 and damage+1 in fierce skirmishes.<br>
<br>
Uruk Pursuer (2/5/3): A cheaper version of the Follower and Hunter, this is the third one card bane for unbound Hobbit decks. This time if an unbound Hobbit is killed you can exert Hunter to maker the Free-Peoples player wound and unbound companion.<br>
<br>
Uruk Runner (3/8/2): A cheaper version of the Chaser, during fierce skirmishes this guy is str+2.<br>
<br>
Uruk Searcher (4/9/2): The first of the Search card abilities. While skirmishing someone with a search card this guy is str+2 and damage+1.<br>
<br>
Uruk Seeker (2/6/2): The second Search card tie-in. While skirmishing someone with a search card this guy is str+2 and damage+1.<br>
<br>
Then for open play you can add this tracker from the Mines of Moria:<br>
<br>
Uruk Scout (3/7/2): Note - this guy is not fierce, he is damage+1. The roaming penalty of all Isengard Minions is 1. If an event is played that spots a ranger, exert this guy to cancel it.<br>
<br>
So there you have it, 11 Two Towers trackers and another one making 12 for open play. Quite a variety to choose from and already an indication of what kind of strategy they revolve around. Obviously it is easy to see that a great deal of them gain extra bonuses in the fierce phase, whilst others are purely counter-strategy cards for unbound Hobbits. Some focus on Search cards and the rest are just about being real mean!<br>
<br>
The first I want to look at is the fierce bonus trackers and the multitude of new ways you can ensure they reach their full potential. Obviously the Free-Peoples player is going to want to knock these guys off the board early so he does not have to deal with them in the fierce phase. So you need to find a way to keep them there and keep them alive. You could always throw in a few Spies of Saruman, but as a general rule I tend to steer away from this card as it is now easily removed and costs a little too much, especially with the likes of Legolas, Dauntless Hunter. So a more practical way is to employ Broad-Bladed sword in combination with Mauhur, this then prevents the tracker form being popped off in any number of ways and you can the prevent all wounds to him in the skirmish with Mauhur. Alternatively you could and more effectively you can remove these trackers from the skirmish and ensure they are able to fight in the fierce phase when they are at their peak. Get Back is a 0 cost event that does exactly that during the assignment phase. Race across the Mark will also perform a similar function for the cost of 2 if you control a site. This way those puny trackers will have a greater chance of inflicting damage and if you add Still They Come then your more beefier fierce bonus minions will be able to add a strength bonus of 3 to a minion stuck in a skirmishimmer all makes an odd kind of sense, but in the case of Uruk Foot Soldier it is blindingly obvious why you would want him alive in the fierce phase with a cost of only 1.<br>
<br>
It all gets even better with the addition of Uglucks Sword. Not only does it provide a wopping str+3 but it allows you to discard a minion to play a minion for a cost of 3. So you can discard you small Uruk Foot Soldier to play Mauhur for free or any of the larger trackers like the Hunter for an incredible low cost considering their abilities. This then provides Ugluck with the resources he needs to change from a poor mans Lurtz to the most cost effective minion in the entire game. At full swing he can be a strength 15, fierce and damage+1 minion for the low cost of 5 (4 for him plus one for his sword). Then if Mauhur is played for free and then an Uruk Runner is played for free you will probably have enough twilight to use Mauhurs abilities to ensure your three minions are alive and kicking for their skirmishes. Then any number of already established pumpers could make the day more painful for your opponent. This is by far the most cost effective way to generate high strength minions.<br>
<br>
There is more to the assignment phase with these nasties too. Brought Back Alive is quite a useful card except that it requires an exertion, all the same it allows you to target a specific unbound companion, of course they can exert to prevent it unless they are an unbound Hobbit. Apart from racking up the fourth trump card for unbound Hobbits in this tracker strategy it provides a way to control more of the assignment phase which flows onto search cards. You can play a whole series of search cards on companions to allow you to force assignments with Uruk Searcher and Uruk Seeker, they are:<br>
<br>
Many Riddles (Cost: 1): Along with providing a 1 to strength you can exert and Isengard Tracker and remove 2 to assign that tracker to the bearer of this condition. Of course the bearer may not be the Ring-Bearer and may also exert to prevent this from occurring.<br>
<br>
Rest While You Can (1): This nasty lays dormant until the companion it is played on dies. At that point you reveal the top 10 cards of the opponents draw deck and you can discard 1 shadow and 1 Free-Peoples card. The deck is then re-shuffled.<br>
<br>
Weary (1): This card will be popular, each time a companion bearing this card is assigned to skirmish the Tracker they must exert. Hey Brough Back Alive could provide some excellent fun with double exertions.<br>
<br>
So instantly you can see the benefits of these search cards, not only do they all have potent abilities, but they provide you with a way to force assignments or simply pile on exertions before the skirmish phase where there will be fierce minions. I hope you can understand now why I really like these guys. This leaves us now with the skirmish phase and the pumpers available to these guys, and that is just it  they are all Uruk-hai and will benefit from all Uruk-hai pumpers. They also have their own in Kill Them Now which makes a tacker str+2 or +4 if they bear a search card and Vengeance which makes a Tracker str+2 for every cards brone by the character it is skirmishing. So those search cards count for Vengeance and they also count for Grima. <br>
<br>
This is pretty much all of it for now, until the next expanion. Taking everything into consideration, a sample deck would be:<br>
<br>
(Cards: 35)<br>
Ugluck, Servant of Saruman x4<br>
Uglucks Sword x3<br>
Mauhur, Patrol Leader x4<br>
Uruk Searcher x3<br>
Uruk Seeker x4<br>
Uruk Foot Soldier x4<br>
Uruk Hunter x2<br>
Weary x4<br>
Many Riddles x2<br>
Kill Them Now x3<br>
Vengeance x1<br>
Brought Back Alive x1<br>
<br>
This would be your standard search card deck that has a focus on forcing assignments and generating exertions and being able to pump your minions. I hope this has given you some ideas for a Tracker deck and there are certainly more things you can do by adding a few different pumpers, but in this case you dont need the traditional power cards like Saruman or Savagery because these guys are already Fierce!<br>
<br>
Have fun!<br>
